Robert McBride was appointed the head of the foreign branch of the State Security Agency. eNCA speaks to political analyst and host of The Fix, Karima Brown for reaction. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Robert McBride is the new Director of the foreign branch of the State Security Agency. President Cyril Ramaphosa announced his approval of this appointment, which is for a 3-year term from 1 July 2020 to 30 June 2023. READ: McBride accuses Nathi Nhleko of scapegoating corruption-busters The position has been vacant for the past four years. State Security Minister, Ayanda Dlodlo, has welcomed the move, saying it will bring organisational stability to the agency. McBride has previously held various political and security positions including as former Chief of Ekurhuleni metro police and Director of the Independent Police Investigative Directorate.